    "explanation": "Retraining the model to re-baseline its performance is the correct answer. When model drift is detected, the recommended action is to retrain the model using updated, higher-quality, or more representative datasets. This process recalibrates the model so that its predictions align with current data patterns and business requirements, effectively re-baselining performance. Retraining helps restore accuracy, relevance, and reliability, and it can be tracked and validated as part of a formal MLOps or AI governance process. Applying manual rule-based overrides to compensate for the drift is incorrect. Introducing manual rules or \"patches\" on top of a drifting model may appear to fix issues quickly, but it does not address the underlying problem: the model's learned patterns no longer match real-world data. Over time, rule-based overrides can become complex, brittle, and hard to maintain, masking deeper accuracy and bias issues. Best practice is to retrain or update the model so its statistical behavior itself is corrected. Temporarily narrowing the model's scope of use without adjusting the training data is incorrect. Limiting where or how a model is used can reduce immediate risk, but it does not resolve model drift. The model will continue to be misaligned with the evolving data environment, and as usage expands again, the same or worse performance problems will reappear. Scope restriction can be a short-term risk control, but recommended practice is to retrain or recalibrate the model based on current data, not simply constrain its deployment. Increasing the model's confidence threshold so fewer predictions are returned is incorrect. Raising the confidence threshold can make the system appear safer but a drifting model can still be confidently wrong if its internal representation is outdated or misaligned. Adjusting thresholds is a tuning step, not a remediation for drift. When monitoring shows true model drift, the underlying model should be retrained or updated to restore trustworthy performance rather than merely filtering its outputs more aggressively."
